🏀🏥 Want to know what Kevin Durant and medical school have in common? 🤔 

Being a team player is essential! 🤝 

Getting into medical school is uber competitive. The margin between getting into med school and getting rejected being very small. Quality letters of recommendation can make all the difference in your application. 📜 

The best way to get a great letter of recommendation is to have people like you, and the best way to get people to like you is to be the ultimate team player, like Durant is being right now. I know the Suns are happy to have him. What are you doing in your premed activities to make people like you?

1.	Try being always willing to lend a hand: Instead of waiting for someone to ask for help, take the initiative to ask people if they need help… even better, assess what they are doing and figure out what they need and offer to provide it.

2.	Try showing your commitment: You’re a busy premed, so it is easy to always be in a rush. Instead, let everyone know that while you are in that activity, you are fully focused and there is no where you would rather be. Maybe show up early, or stay longer than you have to.

3.	Try being the team cheerleader: It is easy to be happy for yourself but try being happy for other members of the team. Look for ways to acknowledge efforts of other members of the team. Or if someone is frustrated, cheer them up by letting them know you believe in them. 

The more likable you are, the better your letters of recommendation will be and the more likely you are to get accepted to med school! 🙌 #TeamPlayer #MedicalSchool #KevinDurant #Success #Premedadvice #premedproductivity #howtogetintomedschool #premedcoach #premedactivities #premedlife #medschool #accepted #letterofrecommendation 
#dominatepremed #drpinesett

As premeds, you have to be extra careful about what you post on social media. 😬 Ja Morant just got suspended from the Memphis Grizzlies for dancing on IG live with a gun 🤦🏾‍♂️🤦🏾‍♂️. Ja has $160 million in the bank, do you? I sure didn’t as a premed, shoot, I don’t have that in my bank account now as a doctor LOL.

As a premed, you can’t afford to turn up, I mean act a fool on social media. Med schools can and will reject you for social media misconduct, so always think twice before posting anything. 🤔

PREMEDS: Do you know how to balance your class schedule to maximize your GPA? 🤔 Don't worry, in this sneak peek from my latest YouTube video I break down a simple 3-step process:

👉 Step 1: Write down all the classes you need to graduate.
👉 Step 2: Categorize them as hard, medium, or easy.
👉 Step 3: Every term, take one hard class, one to two medium classes, and one easy class.

With this simple trick, you can balance your course load every semester and avoid the stress of overwhelming classes! 🙌

SAVE THIS VIDEO and use it to make your own plan.

Then click over to my YouTube channel and watch the full video for more simple processes for balancing classes, premed extra-curricular activities and life in general! 🎓💡

Do high school grades matter for med school? 

Believe it or not, high school grades ARE NOT a good indicator of college success or med school success. 

In fact, studies have demonstrated that more than half of all high school high-achievers struggle with the transition to college! So don't ever get discouraged if your grades aren't the best, most students struggle. 

But the students that get into med school step their game up and improve their grades. 

It is imperative that you learn how to study, how to lean and how to be a high-level test-taker if you want to get into med school because grades and MCAT scores are the only objective measures med schools have to compare students on, so they REALLY MATTER!! 

Plus, you still have to pass all your board exams to remain a doctor... the testing never stops haha. 

Join me tonight on YouTube for a LIVE session, where you can ask me any questions you have. This is FREE premed coaching!!!

I chose to become an anesthesiologist for a lot of reasons, chief among them is that anesthesia is a planning specialty. I’ve gotta study the patient’s history, dial into the surgeon’s needs, and then cook up a foolproof plan to avoid potentially life-threatening issues and navigate that surgery like it’s a walk in the park. That’s right, I’m a master planner—how do you think we anesthesiologists get to chill with crosswords and newspapers all day? 🤣🤣🤣

If you want to get straight A’s and if you want to get into med school, you need to be more like an anesthesiologist and focus on making a sound plan of action. your future #DoctorLife depends on it.

For example, I met with a premed named Tisha this week who had taken the MCAT three times and was sinking fast in her fourth round of prep due to her incessant procrastinating. likeNo plan, no direction—just chaos. We sat down, hashed out a structured daily agenda, and boom! Now, she’s being consistent and making serious strides, well on her way to a solid MCAT score! 📚🚀 

So, tell me, what’s the one thing you desperately need a plan for? Drop it in the comments, and I’ll help you formulate a plan to save your future #Doctorlife 🙌 

#PremedExcellence #AnesthesiaRocks #PlanToDominate #masterplanner #whatsyourplan #premedadvice #premedplan #studentplan #collegeplan #noexcusesjustdominate #mcatplan

In the sea of applicants, med schools are fishing for those with a unique sparkle. 🌟

Med schools crave diversity, not just in demographics, but in experiences, thoughts, and passions. They're not just looking for doctors; they're looking for future leaders, innovators, and compassionate healers who will enrich their campus and the medical field.

When I was a freshman premed, there were lots of cookie cutter extra-curricular opportunities. But I was passionate about helping young students, so I became a mentor and tutor serving as a guardian of potential and a catalyst for change.

It was never about adding another line to my resume. It was about those "aha" moments, the light bulbs that clicked on above their heads, the smiles that spread across their faces when they realized, "Hey, I can do this." It was about showing them that someone believed in them, sometimes even before they believed in themselves.

It was my personal mission that I carried with me into every application and every interview, making it obvious to med schools why they should accept me. Moreover, my passion has remained strong and I’m blessed to continue to live my passion by mentoring and coaching students to this day. 💯

Are you up tossing and turning at night? 😳 

This may be the reason you can’t sleep 💯💯 

Another thing you can do is take a few minutes before bed and write down: 

A) A time slot to accomplish the things you didnt get to today. This will reduce your worrying. 

B) Something you did today you are proud of. This will help reduce the regret you feel about the day. 

C) Something you have coming up that you’re excited about. This will give you a sense of joy and eagerness about your future.

🔴 Out of MCAT practice passages⁉️ 

That means it's time to switch things up and I don’t just mean getting a new set of questions. I’m also talking about switching your approach to questions. Rushing through a million questions, isn’t the way to a top MCAT score. 

IT’S NOT ABOUT HOW MANY QUESTIONS YOU DO, IT’S ABOUT HOW MUCH YOU LEARN FROM EACH QUESTION‼️ 

Once you make the adjustment, find a new set of questions to challenge yourself! Our subconscious can still hold onto familiarity, so don't risk unintentionally repeating questions. 📚
